[11.123067, "i", "cat target_iptables.txt\n"]
[11.123222, "o", "cat target_iptables.txt\r\n"]
[11.123262, "o", "\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[11.124135, "o", "*filter\r\n:INPUT DROP [0:0]\r\n:FORWARD DROP [0:0]\r\n:OUTPUT ACCEPT [0:0]\r\n-A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n-A INPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j ACCEPT\r\nCOMMIT\r\n"]
[11.12429, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[11.124332, "o", "user@494798b68888:~/pentest$ "]
[30.497824, "i", "cat > finding.txt << 'EOF'\nFINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocking Issue\n\nAFFECTED RULES:\nRule 4: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\nRule 5: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\nRule 6: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\nRule 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\n\nROOT CAUSE:\nThe iptables ruleset attempts to implement application-layer filtering at the network layer by using string matching to look for \"Mozilla\" in packet payloads. This is intended to allow only web browsers (which typically have \"Mozilla\" in their User-Agent headers) to access the web services.\n\nWHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP/HTTPS DOESN'T:\n- SSH (port 22): Has an unconditional ACCEPT rule with no string matching requirements\n- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Require the string \"Mozilla\" to be present in the packet payload to be accepted, otherwise packets are explicitly DROPped by subsequent rules\n\nWHY CURL HANGS:\nCurl uses \"curl/<version>\" as its default User-Agent string, n"]
[30.497951, "i", "ot \"Mozilla\". The initial TCP handshake (SYN packets) and subsequent HTTP request packets don't contain \"Mozilla\", so they match the DROP rules instead of the ACCEPT rules. The connection hangs because packets are silently dropped rather than rejected.\n\nPROBLEMS WITH THIS APPROACH:\n1. String matching on packet payloads is inefficient and unreliable for connection filtering\n2. The string \"Mozilla\" may not appear in initial TCP handshake packets, causing legitimate connections to fail\n3. The string matching occurs at the packet level, not the application level, making it timing-dependent\n4. Legitimate tools and automated monitoring systems are blocked\n5. Trivial to bypass - any attacker can simply include \"Mozilla\" in their requests\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nRemove the string matching rules entirely. If access control is needed, implement it at the application layer (web server configuration) using proper authentication, IP whitelisting, or a web application firewall. Network layer filtering should focus on ports and IP"]
[30.497986, "o", "cat > finding.txt << 'EOF'\r\n\u001b[?2004l\rot \"Mozilla\". The initial TCP handshake (SYN packets) and subsequent HTTP request packets do"]
[30.498025, "i", " addresses, not application-layer content.\nEOF\n"]
[30.498074, "o", "n't contain \"Mozilla\", so they match the DROP rules instead of the ACCEPT rules. The connection hangs because packets are silently dropped rather than rejected.\r\n\r\nPROBLEMS WITH THIS APPROACH:\r\n1. String matching on packet payloads is inefficient and unreliable for connection filtering\r\n2. The string \"Mozilla\" may not appear in initial TCP handshake packet"]
[30.498105, "o", "s, causing legitimate connections to fail\r\n3. The string "]
[30.498136, "o", "matching occurs at the packet level, not the application level, making it timing-dependent\r\n4. Legitimate tools and automated monitoring "]
[30.498165, "o", "systems are blocked\r\n5. Trivial to bypass - any attacker can simply include \"Mozilla\" in their requests\r\n\r\nRECOMMENDA"]
[30.498203, "o", "TION:\r\nRemove the string matching rules entirely. If access control is needed, implement it at the application layer (web server configuration) using pr"]
[30.498242, "o", "oper authentication, IP whitelisting, or a web application firewall. Network layer filtering should foc"]
[30.498275, "o", "us on ports and IP addresses, not application-layer content.\r\nEOF\r\n\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.498307, "o", "> "]
[30.498411, "o", "FINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocking Issue\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.498445, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.498479, "o", "\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.498532, "o", "AFFECTED RULES:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.498577, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.498615, "o", "> "]
[30.498835, "o", "Rule 4: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.498869, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.499137, "o", "Rule 5: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.499168, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.499286, "o", "Rule 6: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.499316, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.499343, "o", "> "]
[30.499443, "o", "Rule 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.499474, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.499501, "o", "\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.499531, "o", "> "]
[30.499578, "o", "ROOT CAUSE:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.499616, "o", "> "]
[30.5004, "o", "The iptables ruleset attempts to implement application-layer filtering at the network layer by using string matching to look for \"Mozilla\" in packet payloads. This is intended to allow only web browsers (which typically have \"Mozilla\" in their User-Agent headers) to access the web services.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.500443, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.500471, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.500588, "o", "WHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP/HTTPS DOESN'T:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.50062, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.500858, "o", "- SSH (port 22): Has an unconditional ACCEPT rule with no string matching requirements\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.500886, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.501355, "o", "- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Require the string \"Mozilla\" to be present in the packet payload to be accepted, otherwise packets are explicitly DROPped by subsequent rules\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.50139, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.501426, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.501468, "o", "WHY CURL HANGS:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.501499, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.502372, "o", "Curl uses \"curl/<version>\" as its default User-Agent string, not \"Mozilla\". The initial TCP handshake (SYN packets) and subsequent HTTP request packets don't contain \"Mozilla\", so they match the DROP rules instead of the ACCEPT rules. The connection hangs because packets are silently dropped rather than rejected.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.502409, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.502439, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.502469, "o", "> "]
[30.502522, "o", "PROBLEMS WITH THIS APPROACH:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.502565, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.5026, "o", "> "]
[30.502828, "o", "1. String matching on packet payloads is inefficient and unreliable for connection filtering\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.502861, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.50316, "o", "2. The string \"Mozilla\" may not appear in initial TCP handshake packets, causing legitimate connections to fail\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.503193, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.503477, "o", "3. The string matching occurs at the packet level, not the application level, making it timing-dependent\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.503511, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.50371, "o", "4. Legitimate tools and automated monitoring systems are blocked\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.503746, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.503971, "o", "5. Trivial to bypass - any attacker can simply include \"Mozilla\" in their requests\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.504011, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.504041, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.504077, "o", "RECOMMENDATION:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.504116, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.504976, "o", "Remove the string matching rules entirely. If access control is needed, implement it at the application layer (web server configuration) using proper authentication, IP whitelisting, or a web application firewall. Network layer filtering should focus on ports and IP addresses, not application-layer content.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.505013, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.505045, "o", "EOF\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.509566, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.509605, "o", "user@494798b68888:~/pentest$ "]
[30.60111, "i", "cat finding.txt\n"]
[30.601209, "o", "cat finding.txt\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.602168, "o", "FINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocking Issue\r\n\r\nAFFECTED RULES:\r\nRule 4: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\nRule 5: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\nRule 6: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\nRule 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n\r\nROOT CAUSE:\r\nThe iptables ruleset attempts to implement application-layer filtering at the network layer by using string matching to look for \"Mozilla\" in packet payloads. This is intended to allow only web browsers (which typically have \"Mozilla\" in their User-Agent headers) to access the web services.\r\n\r\nWHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP/HTTPS DOESN'T:\r\n- SSH (port 22): Has an unconditional ACCEPT rule with no string matching requirements\r\n- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Require the string \"Mozilla\" to be present in the packet payload to be accepted, otherwise packets are explicitly DROPped by subsequent rules\r\n\r\nWHY CURL HANGS:\r\nCurl uses \"curl/<version>\" as its default User-Agent string, not \"Mozilla"]
[30.602214, "o", "\". The initial TCP handshake (SYN packets) and subsequent HTTP request packets don't contain \"Mozilla\", so they match the DROP rules instead of the ACCEPT rules. The connection hangs because packets are silently dropped rather than rejected.\r\n\r\nPROBLEMS WITH THIS APPROACH:\r\n1. String matching on packet payloads is inefficient and unreliable for connection filtering\r\n2. The string \"Mozilla\" may not appear in initial TCP handshake packets, causing legitimate connections to fail\r\n3. The string matching occurs at the packet level, not the application level, making it timing-dependent\r\n4. Legitimate tools and automated monitoring systems are blocked\r\n5. Trivial to bypass - any attacker can simply include \"Mozilla\" in their requests\r\n\r\nRECOMMENDATION:\r\nRemove the string matching rules entirely. If access control is needed, implement it at the application layer (web server configuration) using proper authentication, IP whitelisting, or a web application firewall. Network layer filtering should focus on ports and IP "]
[30.602247, "o", "addresses, not application-layer content.\r\n"]
[30.602324, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.602354, "o", "user@494798b68888:~/pentest$ "]
